[32m"Masked text for sample 0, segment 3178-3654: .\n\nLet me try again.\n\nTo solve the problem, we need to apply the given operation @ to the fractions \\(\\frac{7}{30}\\) and \\(\\frac{10}{21}\\). The operation is defined as:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{m}{n} @ \\frac{p}{q} = (m)(p)\\left(\\frac{q}{n}\\right)\n\\]\n\nFor the fractions \\(\\frac{7}{30}\\) and \\(\\frac{10}{21}\\), we can substitute \\(m = 7\\), \\(n = 30\\), \\(p = 10\\), and \\(q = 21\\) into the operation:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{7}{30} @ \\frac{10}{21} = (7)(10)\\left(\\frac{21}{30}\\right)\n\\]\n\nFirst, we simplify \\(\\frac{21}{30}\\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{21}{30} = \\frac{7 \\cdot 3}{10 \\cdot 3} = \\frac{7}{10}\n\\]\n\nSo the expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n(7)(10)\\left(\\frac{7}{10}\\right) = (7)(10)\\left(\\frac{7}{10}\\right) = 7 \\cdot 7 = 49\n\\]\n\nThus, the simplified value of \\(\\frac{7}{30} @ \\frac{10}{21}\\) is \\(49\\).\n\nLet's confirm this with Python code to ensure accuracy.\n```python\n# Define the operation @\ndef operation(m, n, p, q):\n    return (m * p * (q / n))\n\n# Given fractions\nm, n = 7, 30\np, q = 10, 21\n\n# Calculate the result of the operation\nresult = operation(m, n, p, q)\nprint(result)\n```\n```output\n49.0\n```\nThe simplified value of \\(\\frac{7}{30} @ \\frac{10}{21}\\) is \\(\\boxed{49}\\).\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\n"[0m
