[32m'Masked text for sample 0, segment 4939-5489: ]\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\nTo verify whether the given answer is correct, we need to check if the expression \\(10x^2 - x - 24\\) can indeed be factored as \\((Ax - 8)(Bx + 3)\\) and then determine \\(AB + B\\).\n\nFirst, expand the expression \\((Ax - 8)(Bx + 3)\\):\n\n\\[\n(Ax - 8)(Bx + 3) = ABx^2 + 3Ax - 8Bx - 24\n\\]\n\nCombine like terms:\n\n\\[\n= ABx^2 + (3A - 8B)x - 24\n\\]\n\nFor this expression to be equivalent to \\(10x^2 - x - 24\\), the coefficients must match:\n\n1. \\(AB = 10\\)\n2. \\(3A - 8B = -1\\)\n3. The constant term \\(-24\\) matches on both sides.\n\nNow, we need to find integer values of \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) that satisfy these conditions.\n\nFrom \\(AB = 10\\), the possible integer pairs \\((A, B)\\) are:\n- \\((1, 10)\\)\n- \\((2, 5)\\)\n- \\((5, 2)\\)\n- \\((10, 1)\\)\n- \\((-1, -10)\\)\n- \\((-2, -5)\\)\n- \\((-5, -2)\\)\n- \\((-10, -1)\\)\n\nWe need to check which pair satisfies \\(3A - 8B = -1\\).\n\nChecking each pair:\n- For \\((A, B) = (2, 5)\\):\n  \\[\n  3A - 8B = 3(2) - 8(5) = 6 - 40 = -34 \\quad (\\text{not } -1)\n  \\]\n\n- For \\((A, B) = (5, 2)\\):\n  \\[\n  3A - 8B = 3(5) - 8(2) = 15 - 16 = -1 \\quad (\\text{correct})\n  \\]\n\nThus, \\(A = 5\\) and \\(B = 2\\) satisfy both conditions.\n\nNow, calculate \\(AB + B\\):\n\n\\[\nAB + B = 5 \\times 2 + 2 = 10 + 2 = 12\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the given answer \\(12\\) is correct.<|im_end|>\n'[0m
