[32m"Masked text for sample 0, segment 2760-3171: .\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\nTo determine whether the given answer is correct, let's analyze the problem using the properties of logarithms and substitution.\n\nWe have two equations:\n\n1. \\(\\log_6 (x-y) + \\log_6 (x+y) = 2\\)\n2. \\(\\log_y 5x = 2\\)\n\nStarting with the first equation, we can use the property of logarithms that states \\(\\log_b A + \\log_b B = \\log_b (A \\cdot B)\\). Therefore, we can rewrite the equation as:\n\n\\[\n\\log_6 ((x-y)(x+y)) = 2\n\\]\n\nThis implies:\n\n\\[\n(x-y)(x+y) = 6^2 = 36\n\\]\n\nSo, we have:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - y^2 = 36\n\\]\n\nNow, consider the second equation:\n\n\\[\n\\log_y 5x = 2\n\\]\n\nThis implies:\n\n\\[\n5x = y^2\n\\]\n\nNow, we have two equations:\n\n1. \\(x^2 - y^2 = 36\\)\n2. \\(5x = y^2\\)\n\nSubstitute \\(y^2 = 5x\\) into the first equation:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - 5x = 36\n\\]\n\nRearrange this to form a quadratic equation:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - 5x - 36 = 0\n\\]\n\nTo check if \\(x = 9\\) is a solution, substitute \\(x = 9\\) into the quadratic equation:\n\n\\[\n9^2 - 5(9) - 36 = 81 - 45 - 36 = 0\n\\]\n\nSince the equation holds true, \\(x = 9\\) is indeed a solution to the quadratic equation.\n\nTherefore, the given answer \\(x = 9\\) is correct.<|im_end|>\n"[0m
