[32m"Masked text for sample 0, segment 2775-4839: .\n\nLet me try again.\n\nLet's break down the problem step by step. We know that the sum of the numbers on each pair of opposite faces is 7, so the pairs are (1, 6), (2, 5), and (3, 4). Let's denote the probability of rolling face $F$ as $p_F$, and the probability of rolling the face opposite to $F$ as $p_{\\overline{F}}$. All other faces have a probability of $\\frac{1}{6}$.\n\nWe have the following conditions:\n1. $p_F > \\frac{1}{6}$\n2. $p_{\\overline{F}} < \\frac{1}{6}$\n3. The sum of all probabilities is 1, so $p_F + p_{\\overline{F}} + 4 \\cdot \\frac{1}{6} = 1$. This simplifies to $p_F + p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{1}{3}$.\n4. The probability of rolling a sum of 7 with two dice is $\\frac{47}{288}$. The pairs that sum to 7 are (1, 6), (2, 5), (3, 4), (4, 3), (5, 2), and (6, 1). So the probability is given by:\n   \\[\n   p_F \\cdot p_{\\overline{F}} + p_{\\overline{F}} \\cdot p_F + 4 \\cdot \\left(\\frac{1}{6} \\cdot \\frac{1}{6}\\right) = \\frac{47}{288}\n   \\]\n   Simplifying the left side, we get:\n   \\[\n   2p_F p_{\\overline{F}} + \\frac{4}{36} = \\frac{47}{288}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   2p_F p_{\\overline{F}} + \\frac{1}{9} = \\frac{47}{288}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   2p_F p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{47}{288} - \\frac{1}{9}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   2p_F p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{47}{288} - \\frac{32}{288}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   2p_F p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{15}{288}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   p_F p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{15}{576}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   p_F p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{5}{192}\n   \\]\nWe now have two equations:\n1. $p_F + p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{1}{3}$\n2. $p_F p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{5}{192}$\n\nWe can solve these equations using the quadratic formula. Let's denote $p_F = x$ and $p_{\\overline{F}} = \\frac{1}{3} - x$. Then we have:\n\\[\nx \\left(\\frac{1}{3} - x\\right) = \\frac{5}{192}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{x}{3} - x^2 = \\frac{5}{192}\n\\]\n\\[\n192x - 576x^2 = 15\n\\]\n\\[\n576x^2 - 192x + 15 = 0\n\\]\nSo